URCM vs Transformer — Full Detail (Plain Text)

Executive Summary
- URCM uses compact phoneme mapping and μ-convergence telemetry; avoids large embedding tables.
- Transformer systems store large vocabularies and per-token embeddings; memory scales with sequence length.
- Benchmarks indicate ~6,400×–41,600× memory efficiency and strong cached speedups on CPU.

Architecture
- Transformer
  - Representation: discrete tokens; large vocab; next-token prediction
  - Reasoning: learned attention; inference cost grows with sequence length
  - Memory: embedding table O(V×d) + sequence embeddings
  - Determinism: often stochastic; telemetry indirect
- URCM
  - Representation: continuous frequency vectors; compact phoneme set
  - Reasoning: quantifier elimination, typed A*, envelope-based numeric feasibility
  - Memory: small mapping + generated frequency vectors + compact latent state
  - Determinism: deterministic generation; explicit μ/ρ/χ telemetry and principled refusals

